I just don't like when things that could be accessible,

243
00:15:26,452 --> 00:15:26,752
aren't.

244
00:15:28,261 --> 00:15:31,944
I want to start off my section with a quick story.

245
00:15:31,944 --> 00:15:34,927
Once I was talking to someone online about where we thought our

246
00:15:34,927 --> 00:15:37,188
spirits would go when we die.

247
00:15:37,188 --> 00:15:42,373
And I know that sounds like a dark topic to some, but to us, it really wasn't.

248
00:15:42,373 --> 00:15:43,414
It was interesting.

249
00:15:43,414 --> 00:15:47,617
And I remember them saying to me that they wish the afterlife was a library

250
00:15:47,617 --> 00:15:51,120
filled with books of everything that ever happened in history.

251
00:15:51,120 --> 00:15:53,962
And you could just sit down and read it forever.

252
00:15:55,604 --> 00:16:02,729
I jokingly, but also seriously, said, well, I wouldn't wish that because I'm dyslexic.

253
00:16:02,729 --> 00:16:05,592
To which they said, well, you're dyslexic on earth.

254
00:16:05,592 --> 00:16:08,714
That doesn't mean you'd have to be dyslexic in heaven.

255
00:16:08,714 --> 00:16:09,715
My reply?

256
00:16:09,715 --> 00:16:11,896
My dyslexia is a part of me.

257
00:16:11,896 --> 00:16:14,558
I wouldn't want to not be dyslexic in heaven.

258
00:16:14,558 --> 00:16:16,900
That would be losing a part of myself.

259
00:16:16,900 --> 00:16:18,822
I would want heaven to be accessible.

260
00:16:19,825 --> 00:16:23,414
The person I was talking to went silent for a few seconds and said,

261
00:16:23,414 --> 00:16:26,802
you know, I never really thought about disability like that before.

262
00:16:27,701 --> 00:16:33,766
So I hope today that anyone here who assumed anyone disabled would choose to be abled,

263
00:16:33,766 --> 00:16:38,150
if they could, to also rethink the way that you see disability.

264
00:16:38,150 --> 00:16:43,574
When things are made accessible to me, my dyslexia can even become an advantage.

265
00:16:43,574 --> 00:16:46,737
Sure, I'm more likely than my peers to have a typo,

266
00:16:46,737 --> 00:16:50,960
but I'm also better equipped than my peers to check if something is accessible.

267
00:16:52,552 --> 00:16:58,396
Last year I worked on an indie game where our UX UI person, Star St. Germain, shout out,

268
00:16:58,396 --> 00:17:04,600
made an alien font from scratch. It was awesome. One of our mini games involved looking at two

269
00:17:04,600 --> 00:17:09,463
lines of characters and seeing if any of the symbols were mistyped in the second line.

270
00:17:09,463 --> 00:17:13,246
I was the one Star came to to check over all of the symbols and let her know which

271
00:17:13,246 --> 00:17:16,448
ones were too similar or confusing, especially to a dyslexic eye.

272
00:17:17,634 --> 00:17:23,997
We worked together to change the few symbols that needed changing and ended up with a much more accessible game because of it.

273
00:17:23,997 --> 00:17:29,499
Accessibility consulting is powerful and rewarding, and I love doing that.

274
00:17:29,499 --> 00:17:33,720
Now, not to say it's all positive to be dyslexic in games.

275
00:17:33,720 --> 00:17:38,562
I've also had rather poor experiences in gaming due to it, too.

276
00:17:38,562 --> 00:17:41,143
If a game is not accessible, I can't play it.

277
00:17:42,070 --> 00:17:47,512
I have been recommended games and downloaded them only to not be able to read the UI and

278
00:17:47,512 --> 00:17:49,992
have to tell my friends, sorry, I can't play with you.

279
00:17:49,992 --> 00:17:58,074
But you know, that's just how it is sometimes.

280
00:17:58,074 --> 00:18:03,895
And I've also been to cons where I've felt embarrassed that I have to turn away or walk

281
00:18:03,895 --> 00:18:09,677
away from a game demo that somebody is showing or spoken to with derision when I ask a developer

282
00:18:09,677 --> 00:18:11,657
for help with a demo that isn't accessible.

283
00:18:12,297 --> 00:18:17,959
they treat me like a liability. You know, I can tell when I'm being treated by someone in an

284
00:18:17,959 --> 00:18:25,982
ableist manner. It's not hard to pick up on and it's not fun. I admit that I actually cried once

285
00:18:25,982 --> 00:18:32,364
in a demo chair at PAX because I was struggling to play a game and the people weren't helping me

286
00:18:32,364 --> 00:18:39,126
and it was, you know, it was frustrating. I'm not afraid to admit that, like sometimes it is hard.

287
00:18:39,126 --> 00:18:41,467
Yeah, all of that said though.

288
00:18:42,196 --> 00:18:45,699
The silver lining is that every day in this industry,

289
00:18:45,699 --> 00:18:48,101
I want to work towards building a better tomorrow.

290
00:18:48,101 --> 00:18:50,564
And I know that sounds cheesy,

291
00:18:50,564 --> 00:18:53,126
but I really do want to build a better tomorrow

292
00:18:53,126 --> 00:18:57,410
for accessibility, for inclusivity,

293
00:18:57,410 --> 00:19:00,493
so that less people have to feel the bad side

294
00:19:00,493 --> 00:19:00,833
of all of this.

295
00:19:00,833 --> 00:19:04,696
I have brought up several accessibility changes

296
00:19:04,696 --> 00:19:07,019
at both dev and journalism jobs of mine.

297
00:19:07,943 --> 00:19:11,325
And they've gotten implemented relatively quickly

298
00:19:11,325 --> 00:19:12,546
whenever I bring them up.

299
00:19:12,546 --> 00:19:16,508
These changes and step forwards don't just make working a

300
00:19:16,508 --> 00:19:19,710
better experience for me, but also everyone like me

301
00:19:19,710 --> 00:19:24,053
that comes here before or after me.

302
00:19:24,053 --> 00:19:26,454
I'll end this off by saying that.

303
00:19:27,687 --> 00:19:32,028
If y'all ever want to hit me up, my Twitter is right up there.

304
00:19:32,028 --> 00:19:35,968
If you're dyslexic and you want to talk to someone and build community, that's awesome.

305
00:19:35,968 --> 00:19:40,049
If you're not and you just have questions or anything you want to say, feel free.

306
00:19:40,049 --> 00:19:41,910
My DMs are always open.

307
00:19:41,910 --> 00:19:47,251
And last but not least, dyslexic folks in gaming, untie.

308
00:19:47,251 --> 00:19:48,931
Sorry, sorry.

309
00:19:48,931 --> 00:19:49,231
Unite.

310
00:19:49,231 --> 00:19:50,532
Thank you.

311
00:20:00,502 --> 00:20:07,206
All right, next up, I'd like to introduce our first remote guest of the night,

312
00:20:07,206 --> 00:20:10,808
the wonderful Cameron Hopkinson.

313
00:20:10,808 --> 00:20:11,129
Thank you.

314
00:20:11,129 --> 00:20:16,012
Good morning, everyone.

315
00:20:16,012 --> 00:20:20,274
It is currently 6 a.m. here, so if I seem a little drowsy, please bear with me.

316
00:20:20,274 --> 00:20:23,796
So my name is Cameron.

317
00:20:23,796 --> 00:20:28,319
I am a Game Access Push consultant, composer and programmer from New Zealand,

318
00:20:28,319 --> 00:20:29,420
and I am autistic.

319
00:20:30,337 --> 00:20:35,201
Attending events such as conferences and networking events is often described as crucial for anyone

320
00:20:35,201 --> 00:20:40,244
looking at breaking into the games industry, yet I have struggled a lot at events due to

321
00:20:40,244 --> 00:20:41,645
being autistic.

322
00:20:41,645 --> 00:20:45,688
This will be a quick chat about a few things that events can do and have done that will

323
00:20:45,688 --> 00:20:48,570
help make them more manageable.

324
00:20:48,570 --> 00:20:56,636
I am going to focus on in-person events just because of time.

325
00:21:00,192 --> 00:21:02,713
Also, my setup is to do no fault of GDC a bit,

326
00:21:02,713 --> 00:21:04,754
so bear with me for that as well.

327
00:21:04,754 --> 00:21:07,194
But first, a quick disclaimer.

328
00:21:07,194 --> 00:21:13,496
Autism is a disability that has a vast number of symptoms.

329
00:21:13,496 --> 00:21:16,237
Severity of each of these symptoms

330
00:21:16,237 --> 00:21:19,858
varies partly from autistic person to autistic person.

331
00:21:19,858 --> 00:21:21,659
Text speaking, there are some autistic people

332
00:21:21,659 --> 00:21:22,859
that are nonverbal.

333
00:21:22,859 --> 00:21:24,060
They cannot talk at all.

334
00:21:24,813 --> 00:21:28,295
There are some like me who have what is called selective mutism,

335
00:21:28,295 --> 00:21:30,737
where we cannot talk in certain situations,

336
00:21:30,737 --> 00:21:35,220
and there are autistic people that have absolutely no problem speaking whatsoever.

337
00:21:35,220 --> 00:21:40,844
While there is a lot of overlap in our collective autistic experiences,

338
00:21:40,844 --> 00:21:43,746
there is no universal autistic experience.

339
00:21:43,746 --> 00:21:47,009
Not everything in this talk is going to apply to every autistic person,

340
00:21:47,009 --> 00:21:49,370
but taking the following into consideration

341
00:21:49,370 --> 00:21:51,872
will help make your events more accessible to autistic people.

342
00:21:57,871 --> 00:22:03,597
One thing that you can do to make your events more accessible for autistic people is to have a dedicated quiet area.

343
00:22:03,597 --> 00:22:09,162
This gives people a space to go if they need to decompress because everything has gotten to be too much.

344
00:22:09,162 --> 00:22:13,586
This kind of space can easily be the difference between an autistic person having a meltdown or not.

345
00:22:13,586 --> 00:22:17,150
So if you're running an event, please consider having a dedicated quiet area.

346
00:22:17,878 --> 00:22:22,122
The only thing to keep in mind with this is that there will need to be people there to enforce it.

347
00:22:22,122 --> 00:22:26,225
Otherwise you risk the room simply becoming another space for networking,

348
00:22:26,225 --> 00:22:29,107
which kind of defeats the purpose of that space.

349
00:22:29,107 --> 00:22:35,491
If you're hosting a networking event, avoid playing music.

350
00:22:35,491 --> 00:22:39,514
When I have gone to networking events that have played music,

351
00:22:39,514 --> 00:22:42,777
it has generally just made the event louder.

352
00:22:42,777 --> 00:22:46,199
It can get harder to make out what anybody is saying.

353
00:22:46,842 --> 00:22:50,243
A lot of autistic people have auditory processing difficulties.

354
00:22:50,243 --> 00:22:56,425
They make it hard to make out what a person is saying if lots of other people are speaking.

355
00:22:56,425 --> 00:23:02,706
And everyone yelling louder to be heard over everyone just worsens the issue.

356
00:23:02,706 --> 00:23:07,607
And it's not like the music will be audible for anyone or people trying to yell over it anyway.

357
00:23:07,607 --> 00:23:10,108
If an event is a party, then feel free to play music.

358
00:23:10,108 --> 00:23:14,569
But if the aim of the event is for people to network, please keep it off.

359
00:23:18,466 --> 00:23:26,452
Incense and flashlights, which can be a feature of all shows and other occasions, can be highly

360
00:23:26,452 --> 00:23:32,256
distressing to autistic people and can easily lead to meltdowns. One way to make your event more

361
00:23:32,256 --> 00:23:37,240
accessible to autistic people is to avoid these if at all possible. Another reason to avoid flashing

362
00:23:37,240 --> 00:23:41,603
lights is because of the risk of seizures for people that have epilepsy, which happens to be a

363
00:23:41,603 --> 00:23:47,968
common comorbidity for autistic people, which means a lot of autistic people also have epilepsy.

364
00:23:48,867 --> 00:23:53,670
Seizures are serious and can easily lead to serious injury, so minimizing the risk that

365
00:23:53,670 --> 00:23:59,593
someone could have a seizure is very important, not only just for the sake of your attendees,

366
00:23:59,593 --> 00:24:03,095
but for the sake of your wallet because lawsuits can and do happen.

367
00:24:03,095 --> 00:24:14,582
Another way to make your event more accessible is to restrict the number of people who attend.

368
00:24:14,903 --> 00:24:20,845
A lot of game dev events will try and shove as many people into a space as physically possible,

369
00:24:20,845 --> 00:24:27,127
which makes events inaccessible to us for two reasons. The first is that the event,

370
00:24:27,127 --> 00:24:30,708
it means the event becomes a lot of people trying to yell over each other,

371
00:24:30,708 --> 00:24:35,970
which as I've explained already, is an issue. The second reason is that it makes it near

372
00:24:35,970 --> 00:24:38,370
impossible to move around without people bumping into you.

373
00:24:39,452 --> 00:24:43,176
Generally, autistic people do not like being touched unexpectedly.

374
00:24:43,176 --> 00:24:46,078
Filling your event up to fire capacity makes this inevitable.

375
00:24:46,078 --> 00:24:51,583
Also, restricting the number of people at your event helps physically disabled people,

376
00:24:51,583 --> 00:24:55,366
as it is near impossible to move around a cramped venue using mobility aids

377
00:24:55,366 --> 00:24:57,068
such as a walking stick and a wheelchair.

378
00:25:02,928 --> 00:25:06,730
Something I've seen some conferences do is have stickers at registration that

379
00:25:06,730 --> 00:25:10,851
they can play that attendees can place on their badges to tell people what kind of

380
00:25:10,851 --> 00:25:14,573
interactions they're comfortable with. For example, you can have stickers to

381
00:25:14,573 --> 00:25:18,514
indicate whether you're okay with hugs, just handshake, or if you want people to not touch

382
00:25:18,514 --> 00:25:23,276
you at all. You could also have stickers about whether you would want people to

383
00:25:23,276 --> 00:25:26,537
start conversations with you or whether you just want to be left alone.

384
00:25:27,081 --> 00:25:30,122
This is great for autistic people for multiple reasons.

385
00:25:30,122 --> 00:25:32,742
First of all, it lets autistic people easily dictate

386
00:25:32,742 --> 00:25:35,543
how much contact they want with others.

387
00:25:35,543 --> 00:25:37,943
A lot of autistic people do not like being hugged,

388
00:25:37,943 --> 00:25:39,803
especially by people they don't know.

389
00:25:39,803 --> 00:25:43,024
So having something on your badge to tell people

390
00:25:43,024 --> 00:25:45,004
not to hug you will help keep that from happening.

391
00:25:45,004 --> 00:25:47,945
Secondly, it makes it easier for autistic people

392
00:25:47,945 --> 00:25:49,885
to initiate conversations with people.

393
00:25:49,885 --> 00:25:53,366
A lot of us struggle with social cues and neurotypical people,

394
00:25:53,366 --> 00:25:54,806
so it can be hard to determine

395
00:25:54,806 --> 00:25:56,367
if someone is wanting to chat or not.

396
00:25:56,852 --> 00:26:03,834
these stickers can help misguide that awkwardness.

397
00:26:03,834 --> 00:26:09,076
Anyway, that is a small and non-exhaustive list of things that can be done to help make events more accessible.

398
00:26:09,076 --> 00:26:17,258
Hopefully that helps some of you who are looking at organizing events in the future.

399
00:26:17,258 --> 00:26:19,199
And that is me.

400
00:26:19,199 --> 00:26:20,479
And yeah, if you want to...

401
00:26:21,880 --> 00:26:23,824
I won't be at Q&A afterwards because it's virtual.

402
00:26:23,824 --> 00:26:26,568
So feel free to reach out to me if you have any questions

403
00:26:26,568 --> 00:26:28,372
or anything like that.

404
00:26:28,372 --> 00:26:30,575
Otherwise, I will pass on to Emily.

405
00:26:45,030 --> 00:26:47,031
Hi, my name is Emily Stel.

406
00:26:47,031 --> 00:26:50,454
I'm going to talk a bit about my journey and career

407
00:26:50,454 --> 00:26:53,097
in the industry.

408
00:26:53,097 --> 00:26:53,297
Sorry.

409
00:26:53,297 --> 00:26:55,979
I'm going to talk a bit about my personal experiences finding

410
00:26:55,979 --> 00:26:59,102
employment and self-acceptance through games.

411
00:26:59,102 --> 00:27:04,807
I'm at the very start of my journey and career

412
00:27:04,807 --> 00:27:05,788
in the industry in general.

413
00:27:05,788 --> 00:27:10,612
And actually, I'm at the very start of my.

414
00:27:11,675 --> 00:27:14,819
journey and career in the industry and actually work in general.

415
00:27:14,819 --> 00:27:19,545
Last year I started my first job ever as a junior game designer back home in the UK.

416
00:27:19,545 --> 00:27:26,194
I'm also artistic. It's one of my professional and professional goals

417
00:27:26,194 --> 00:27:29,818
to one day be able to say that without all the accompanying anxiety.

418
00:27:30,822 --> 00:27:34,725
There's still a lot of stigma and misconceptions surrounding autism,

419
00:27:34,725 --> 00:27:38,488
and I even worry that being openly autistic could hurt my career,

420
00:27:38,488 --> 00:27:42,191
especially as a designer where communication is such a key thing.

421
00:27:42,191 --> 00:27:46,695
I spent a few years not in employment, education or training,

422
00:27:46,695 --> 00:27:49,958
and the word communication became something of a spectre for me.

423
00:27:49,958 --> 00:27:54,081
As an autistic person, it's easy to look through job descriptions

424
00:27:54,081 --> 00:27:58,244
and see requirements like excellent communication skills

425
00:27:58,244 --> 00:28:00,066
and think, well...

426
00:28:00,556 --> 00:28:05,800
that excludes me, but there's something that took me some time to figure out.

427
00:28:05,800 --> 00:28:09,904
Finding something difficult isn't actually the same thing as being bad at it.

428
00:28:09,904 --> 00:28:16,129
But how can someone with a condition that's usually characterized by a deficit in social

429
00:28:16,129 --> 00:28:23,555
communication actually be good at communication? Well, part of it is practice. Perhaps I've

430
00:28:23,555 --> 00:28:26,557
gained these skills a little slower than most people.

431
00:28:26,881 --> 00:28:31,443
but I can still learn and grow and improve, even in difficult areas.

432
00:28:31,443 --> 00:28:33,883
Part of it is sheer force of will.

433
00:28:33,883 --> 00:28:38,165
Struggling with something often means spending a lot more time thinking about it

434
00:28:38,165 --> 00:28:39,385
than the average person.

435
00:28:39,385 --> 00:28:42,547
And a big part of it is that

436
00:28:42,547 --> 00:28:45,608
communication is a really big concept

437
00:28:45,608 --> 00:28:49,149
and not all of it is actually required to be effective in employment.

438
00:28:50,204 --> 00:28:54,628
So I might not always remember to ask you how your day was,

439
00:28:54,628 --> 00:28:57,991
but I can communicate my ideas about video games effectively.

440
00:28:57,991 --> 00:29:04,216
All right, so maybe finding communication difficult

441
00:29:04,216 --> 00:29:07,538
doesn't actually exclude me from being a game designer.

442
00:29:07,538 --> 00:29:10,721
Is it possible that being autistic

443
00:29:10,721 --> 00:29:13,203
makes me a better game designer?

444
00:29:13,777 --> 00:29:19,861
This is a slightly difficult issue for me. I think there's a tendency in businesses to advocate for

445
00:29:19,861 --> 00:29:25,204
diversity exclusively because of the benefits it can bring, but there's still an argument to be

446
00:29:25,204 --> 00:29:31,088
made that the advantages are irrelevant, and including more people is reason enough to do

447
00:29:31,088 --> 00:29:38,253
something, but I won't push that point too hard right now. Because there are many positive traits

448
00:29:38,253 --> 00:29:42,836
associated with autism, and a lot of them are very useful in game design.

449
00:29:43,581 --> 00:29:48,263
things like curiosity, creativity, and attention to detail.

450
00:29:48,263 --> 00:29:50,725
But for me, it's passion.

451
00:29:50,725 --> 00:29:54,147
I've never been as interested in anything

452
00:29:54,147 --> 00:29:55,828
as much as I am in video games.

453
00:29:56,719 --> 00:30:01,261
And I used to think that was quite sad, like some kind of personal failing.

454
00:30:01,261 --> 00:30:05,842
But now, to have the opportunity to channel that passion into a career and a purpose,

455
00:30:05,842 --> 00:30:10,083
I find it's actually a strength that helps me in my role every day.

456
00:30:10,083 --> 00:30:15,825
And for me, that passion runs so deep that I don't think I could do anything else.

457
00:30:15,825 --> 00:30:24,328
Starting work in the games industry has been both the hardest and the best thing I've ever done in my life.

458
00:30:25,387 --> 00:30:29,790
I spent a lot of years thinking I wasn't capable of very much.

459
00:30:29,790 --> 00:30:34,974
Receiving my first job offer was a real turning point for me, and it wasn't until that moment

460
00:30:34,974 --> 00:30:37,436
that I actually wondered if I could do it.

461
00:30:37,436 --> 00:30:43,720
Through finding a place in the game industry, I was able to start on a path of wondering

462
00:30:43,720 --> 00:30:47,083
what else I might be able to do that I didn't think was possible.

463
00:30:47,083 --> 00:30:50,906
Just being here is a pretty big one.

464
00:30:51,408 --> 00:30:56,431
Employment, or the right employment, can have such a positive impact on a person's life,

465
00:30:56,431 --> 00:31:03,134
but it's unfortunately something that's just inaccessible to most autistic people.

466
00:31:03,134 --> 00:31:07,616
I would really love for as many people to be able to find their own place,

467
00:31:07,616 --> 00:31:11,338
and I hope that the games industry can be one of those places for more people.

468
00:31:14,334 --> 00:31:18,759
So if you would also like to try and help make a place for autistic people,

469
00:31:18,759 --> 00:31:22,364
I have a few really simple points that anyone can think about.

470
00:31:22,364 --> 00:31:26,990
Patience and awareness.

471
00:31:26,990 --> 00:31:32,137
A big struggle for me on a daily basis is being perceived as rude when I don't mean to be.

