Everyone's ADHD is different, which is why I've asked other game devs with ADHD to review this talk.

715
00:44:02,635 --> 00:44:05,198
For starters, these are some of my symptoms.

716
00:44:05,198 --> 00:44:07,400
Inattention.

717
00:44:08,384 --> 00:44:12,628
Our nervous system is actually interest-based rather than importance-based.

718
00:44:12,628 --> 00:44:15,270
Really, anything that breaks consistency.

719
00:44:15,270 --> 00:44:19,795
Neurotypical people go into 30-minute Twitter rabbit holes a few times a day.

720
00:44:19,795 --> 00:44:26,121
ADHDers do this every 30 minutes and forget their job interviews and anniversary dates before breakfast.

721
00:44:26,121 --> 00:44:29,725
Also, breakfast. We forget breakfast a lot.

722
00:44:29,725 --> 00:44:32,267
We understand the work, but the context can disappear.

723
00:44:33,602 --> 00:44:37,545
Hyperactivity, I won't realize I'm tapping my foot

724
00:44:37,545 --> 00:44:40,927
during a meeting until someone gets mad about it.

725
00:44:40,927 --> 00:44:44,169
Impulsivity, what to eat, what to wear.

726
00:44:44,169 --> 00:44:46,651
I just acquired a rabbit farm in Nebraska.

727
00:44:46,651 --> 00:44:48,652
It varies depending on the day.

728
00:44:48,652 --> 00:44:51,314
At work, this means I get excited by ideas

729
00:44:51,314 --> 00:44:53,416
and interrupt people in meetings,

730
00:44:53,416 --> 00:44:54,957
and then I apologize often.

731
00:44:56,477 --> 00:45:03,000
So far, these are common symptoms that probably fit your image of ADHD, but what kind of person

732
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:08,943
loves note-taking, proactively organizes, focuses like nothing else, and does well in group settings?

733
00:45:08,943 --> 00:45:14,305
All of these are actually coping mechanisms that I've had to learn over the years.

734
00:45:14,305 --> 00:45:17,827
They're examples of masking ADHD, like Jade talked about earlier.

735
00:45:18,824 --> 00:45:23,665
I have working memory issues, so if I can't keep up with my notes, I'm totally lost.

736
00:45:23,665 --> 00:45:28,947
I'm a proactive organizer because I get overwhelmed by a bunch of raw data without filters.

737
00:45:28,947 --> 00:45:34,168
I get into these hours-long flow states where I just forget about everything and it's another

738
00:45:34,168 --> 00:45:37,009
rabbit hole and hopefully I haven't forgotten about another job interview.

739
00:45:37,936 --> 00:45:40,158
I have difficulty reflecting internally.

740
00:45:40,158 --> 00:45:42,600
Lots of people benefit from a group brainstorm,

741
00:45:42,600 --> 00:45:44,801
but I don't even realize I need to brainstorm

742
00:45:44,801 --> 00:45:47,683
until it's too late.

743
00:45:47,683 --> 00:45:49,625
By comparison, solo projects

744
00:45:49,625 --> 00:45:51,446
also become difficult and boring.

745
00:45:51,446 --> 00:45:53,348
All that being said,

746
00:45:53,348 --> 00:45:55,770
please challenge your expectations

747
00:45:55,770 --> 00:45:57,871
of what ADHD coworkers are good at

748
00:45:57,871 --> 00:45:59,312
while understanding how much work

749
00:45:59,312 --> 00:46:01,494
it can take us to compensate.

750
00:46:01,494 --> 00:46:04,476
To remove barriers for people with ADHD,

751
00:46:04,476 --> 00:46:07,178
we need structure, consistency.

752
00:46:07,822 --> 00:46:13,824
and care. Structure, bear with me on this. I'm about to rehash a Fast Company article that you've

753
00:46:13,824 --> 00:46:17,966
definitely already read too many times, but this is important. Without structure,

754
00:46:17,966 --> 00:46:24,769
I am a hot pile of garbage. Let's try to keep meetings short. I fade around 40 minutes. If

755
00:46:24,769 --> 00:46:31,011
you have to go long, have breaks with snacks. Have a clear agenda that's shared beforehand

756
00:46:31,011 --> 00:46:33,132
so we have time to prepare and freak out.

757
00:46:33,967 --> 00:46:40,912
I may take my own notes, but it's good for everyone to agree where meeting minutes will be stored and who's taking them.

758
00:46:40,912 --> 00:46:46,216
Give as much notice for meetings as possible and allow people to choose when they present.

759
00:46:46,216 --> 00:46:53,781
I have difficulty focusing when I'm thinking about what I want to say. It's better to share my work first so I can focus on note taking for the rest of the meeting.

760
00:46:53,781 --> 00:46:55,803
Consistency.

761
00:46:57,485 --> 00:46:57,785
Right here.

762
00:46:57,785 --> 00:47:00,366
If you need me to do something that's important,

763
00:47:00,366 --> 00:47:03,308
a physical reminder is my last line of defense

764
00:47:03,308 --> 00:47:04,249
against my ADHD.

765
00:47:04,249 --> 00:47:07,311
I like it when people give me an urgent task

766
00:47:07,311 --> 00:47:08,892
and have a post-it reminder to go with it,

767
00:47:08,892 --> 00:47:11,633
but please check with your ADHD coworkers.

768
00:47:11,633 --> 00:47:14,635
It can come off as super passive aggressive,

769
00:47:14,635 --> 00:47:17,117
like a post-it war with a roommate.

770
00:47:17,117 --> 00:47:20,499
If you're working remotely, send me a message.

771
00:47:20,499 --> 00:47:20,759
Not yet.

772
00:47:20,759 --> 00:47:23,661
If you're working remotely, send me a message

773
00:47:23,661 --> 00:47:25,101
after you add that JIRA ticket.

774
00:47:25,101 --> 00:47:26,342
It's like a digital post-it.

775
00:47:27,775 --> 00:47:32,877
Kanban boards like Trello are great visual tools to organize tons of information into bite-sized cards.

776
00:47:32,877 --> 00:47:41,800
A couple of notes here. When people go outside these systems, I lose tasks and forget them. So please use them.

777
00:47:41,800 --> 00:47:45,841
Plenty of talented ADHDers find project management software overwhelming.

778
00:47:45,841 --> 00:47:50,562
Try not to make these systems a hiring requirement and be willing to train new hires.

779
00:47:51,988 --> 00:47:56,290
I structured my day into big blocks of time to enable flow states.

780
00:47:56,290 --> 00:47:59,531
Emily told me flow states are like beautiful jam sessions.

781
00:47:59,531 --> 00:48:04,254
Interruptions are like a record scratch that makes the beat almost unrecoverable.

782
00:48:04,254 --> 00:48:08,676
There's this thing called the switch cost effect, where even neurotypical people

783
00:48:08,676 --> 00:48:12,698
take 23 minutes to recover their focus after an interruption, as small

784
00:48:12,698 --> 00:48:14,078
as a random text message.

785
00:48:14,847 --> 00:48:22,995
Plan check-ins and meetings, encourage everyone to set up office hour availability, and don't push those boundaries unless it's an emergency.

786
00:48:22,995 --> 00:48:30,442
Care. Folks with ADHD do stuff that in our non-ADHD-friendly world can come across as rude.

787
00:48:30,442 --> 00:48:36,267
For example, I often don't make eye contact with people during conversations because I can get distracted by facial expressions.

788
00:48:36,987 --> 00:48:41,248
During meetings, I may work on an art task or a sketch.

789
00:48:41,248 --> 00:48:43,288
Doodling actually helps me focus on you.

790
00:48:43,288 --> 00:48:46,189
Think of it like spare processing capacity

791
00:48:46,189 --> 00:48:49,310
that if unused starts working on another task.

792
00:48:49,310 --> 00:48:51,390
I need to keep myself engaged with something

793
00:48:51,390 --> 00:48:54,891
or it'll take over every spare process.

794
00:48:54,891 --> 00:48:57,311
In the office, if I'm wearing headphones,

795
00:48:57,311 --> 00:48:58,712
yes, I am ignoring you.

796
00:48:58,712 --> 00:49:00,512
And no, it's not personal.

797
00:49:00,512 --> 00:49:03,032
Sometimes I'll even turn off messaging software.

798
00:49:03,032 --> 00:49:05,213
All of this is to help me get my work done.

799
00:49:06,417 --> 00:49:14,661
Speaking to managers here, many of us prefer to sit in quiet areas that aren't near an entrance or busy area for obvious reasons.

800
00:49:14,661 --> 00:49:27,207
And lastly, let's just say what we mean. Alyssa Sweetman told me how the anxiety of guessing intent in a workplace that's filled with jargon stressed her out every day.

801
00:49:27,207 --> 00:49:33,290
Bottom line, do your research and check in with your ADHD colleagues, as well as your neurotypical co-workers.

802
00:49:33,863 --> 00:49:40,847
Some may be keeping their ADHD to themselves, so it's important to remember that this is private medical information.

803
00:49:40,847 --> 00:49:44,490
I know I've had mine because I worry it'll keep me from getting hired somewhere.

804
00:49:44,490 --> 00:49:50,774
And giving this talk has been a pretty big milestone in accepting my ADHD. So thank you for listening.

805
00:49:50,774 --> 00:49:57,718
A special note to the people, a special thank you note to the people that offered me feedback on this talk and gave me permission to give them a shout out.

