815
00:50:37,641 --> 00:50:39,222
and his kids.

816
00:50:39,222 --> 00:50:42,524
I'm 35 years old, and I'm an Unreal Engine fanatic

817
00:50:42,524 --> 00:50:44,126
since the Unreal Development Kit in 2004.

818
00:50:44,126 --> 00:50:48,388
I'm the project lead on digitally adapted training,

819
00:50:48,388 --> 00:50:50,550
a collaboration with Norway's largest specialist hospital,

820
00:50:50,550 --> 00:50:54,232
and the founder of AECRE and Wise Urban Studios.

821
00:50:54,818 --> 00:50:58,501
We do rapid prototypes, consultancy, and also medical software.

822
00:50:58,501 --> 00:51:04,166
And today I will talk to you about the ethical responsibility of accessibility.

823
00:51:04,166 --> 00:51:06,268
So, oh, sorry.

824
00:51:06,268 --> 00:51:11,232
It all started with a friend of mine suffering a brain stroke in his 40s.

825
00:51:11,232 --> 00:51:16,696
His drive and iron will to rehabilitate made me look into the possibilities of games in brain trauma rehabilitation.

826
00:51:17,900 --> 00:51:20,461
Back in 2019, I pitched an idea to the large specialist

827
00:51:20,461 --> 00:51:22,543
hospital here.

828
00:51:22,543 --> 00:51:25,324
My idea was to reinvent how we approach brain trauma

829
00:51:25,324 --> 00:51:29,127
rehabilitation and how we develop games for it.

830
00:51:29,127 --> 00:51:32,209
By developing a VR framework for accessibility that allowed us

831
00:51:32,209 --> 00:51:34,590
to tweak and adjust features for each individual patient

832
00:51:34,590 --> 00:51:37,152
to their specific needs, we managed

833
00:51:37,152 --> 00:51:39,233
to include patients that normally wouldn't be able

834
00:51:39,233 --> 00:51:41,055
to play games in rehabilitation.

835
00:51:42,453 --> 00:51:45,534
Traumatic brain injury and stroke patients often exhibit

836
00:51:45,534 --> 00:51:46,875
neurodiverse traits.

837
00:51:46,875 --> 00:51:50,117
They may have aphasia, lack of concentration, or disordered

838
00:51:50,117 --> 00:51:51,978
vision, loss of hearing.

839
00:51:51,978 --> 00:51:54,059
And for us to include everyone, we made several

840
00:51:54,059 --> 00:52:00,002
systems, some of which are quite normal in games today.

841
00:52:00,002 --> 00:52:04,064
So we created minigames based on the feedback from health

842
00:52:04,064 --> 00:52:06,665
care personnel and from patients using the

843
00:52:06,665 --> 00:52:08,867
accessibility framework that we built.

844
00:52:10,583 --> 00:52:14,905
VR games and VR games, they see up to 200% increased

845
00:52:14,905 --> 00:52:16,105
engagement in training.

846
00:52:16,105 --> 00:52:17,166
So this is very important.

847
00:52:17,166 --> 00:52:22,808
And here are some of the systems that we did create

848
00:52:22,808 --> 00:52:24,568
for the project.

849
00:52:24,568 --> 00:52:29,090
We had individual VR control schemes like AutoGrab,

850
00:52:29,090 --> 00:52:30,230
HoldToGrab, ClickToGrab.

851
00:52:30,672 --> 00:52:34,097
in order to meet the mouse of people with paralysis.

852
00:52:34,097 --> 00:52:36,900
Games are also playable with one arm, and we can toggle a

853
00:52:36,900 --> 00:52:39,844
switch to convert the right controller into the left

854
00:52:39,844 --> 00:52:40,865
controller if needed.

855
00:52:40,865 --> 00:52:45,571
For visual adjustments, we had highlighted colors and

856
00:52:45,571 --> 00:52:48,735
gameplay and elements like high contrast and easy to read

857
00:52:48,735 --> 00:52:49,637
fonts with voiceover.

858
00:52:50,442 --> 00:52:56,604
after TBI or stroke, up to 30 to 40 percent of the people have impaired vision. And visibility,

859
00:52:56,604 --> 00:53:01,185
improving visibility and adding voiceover helped our users quickly identify important

860
00:53:01,185 --> 00:53:08,447
information. But also immersion is very important. We avoided artificial things like omnipresent

861
00:53:08,447 --> 00:53:14,208
voices. Rather everything comes from a natural source in the world. And this is more comfortable

862
00:53:14,208 --> 00:53:19,010
and is less disconcerting for people, especially those that struggle with attention.

863
00:53:20,217 --> 00:53:23,542
Another important element was creating a relaxing environment.

864
00:53:23,542 --> 00:53:29,351
We built our world with relaxing colors, a tropical island with a cozy beach, sunbeds,

865
00:53:29,351 --> 00:53:33,036
books, fruits, and other things you'd normally associate with relaxing.

866
00:53:33,036 --> 00:53:36,462
This was important for us to sell the illusion to our users.

867
00:53:38,772 --> 00:53:40,534
We also avoided having distracting colors

868
00:53:40,534 --> 00:53:41,835
and clutter in our world.

869
00:53:41,835 --> 00:53:44,537
Finding a balance between believable and overwhelming

870
00:53:44,537 --> 00:53:47,399
can be challenging, but with the help of early workshops

871
00:53:47,399 --> 00:53:51,802
during development, we were able to strike a balance early.

872
00:53:51,802 --> 00:53:55,185
And the early hands-on experience with our user

873
00:53:55,185 --> 00:53:57,506
was paramount to achieving our goal.

874
00:53:57,506 --> 00:54:00,769
Cluttered and overwhelming worlds, loud sounds,

875
00:54:00,769 --> 00:54:03,651
flashy imagery, omnipresent sounds,

876
00:54:03,651 --> 00:54:05,452
and out-of-place elements can be very hard

877
00:54:05,452 --> 00:54:06,813
for neurodivergent users.

878
00:54:07,898 --> 00:54:10,300
The infamous 100% volume splash screen

879
00:54:10,300 --> 00:54:11,701
still haunts games to this day

880
00:54:11,701 --> 00:54:14,303
and can cause problems for a lot of players,

881
00:54:14,303 --> 00:54:16,104
especially those that are neurodivergent.

882
00:54:16,104 --> 00:54:19,686
Some are even exhausted before they start to play the game.

883
00:54:19,686 --> 00:54:20,366
This is not good.

884
00:54:20,366 --> 00:54:24,789
We have to think diversely about our games

885
00:54:24,789 --> 00:54:27,651
and adding features that help neurodiverse players

886
00:54:27,651 --> 00:54:30,513
in any games, not just applied games, is very important.

887
00:54:30,513 --> 00:54:34,596
I encourage everyone here to think about accessibility

888
00:54:34,596 --> 00:54:34,716
to a

889
00:54:36,167 --> 00:54:41,588
neurodiverse scope, not just the normal scope of accessibility.

890
00:54:41,588 --> 00:54:46,090
After all, there is 1.2 billion people that are neurodivergent.

891
00:54:46,090 --> 00:54:50,671
So, why is this an ethical issue and why should you care?

892
00:54:50,671 --> 00:54:56,552
Well, the lack of diverse accessibility features in games

893
00:54:56,552 --> 00:55:00,313
isn't just a gameplay issue, it is an ethical issue. It excludes

894
00:55:00,313 --> 00:55:04,434
people from partaking in an activity that brings all layers of society together.

895
00:55:05,547 --> 00:55:07,487
Not only in applied games, but in all games.

896
00:55:07,487 --> 00:55:10,968
While we still face challenges with internet connectivity

897
00:55:10,968 --> 00:55:13,888
and hardware quality, games has the potential

898
00:55:13,888 --> 00:55:16,989
to be the place where you can socialize as equals,

899
00:55:16,989 --> 00:55:18,909
where social constructs and barriers

900
00:55:18,909 --> 00:55:20,109
doesn't have to hinder us.

901
00:55:20,109 --> 00:55:23,290
If we want a diverse and understanding tomorrow,

902
00:55:23,290 --> 00:55:24,530
we need to experience each other

903
00:55:24,530 --> 00:55:26,450
without limitations and prejudice.

904
00:55:26,450 --> 00:55:29,911
This will be even more important as the metaverse,

905
00:55:29,911 --> 00:55:32,632
whatever shape or form that will take, becomes reality.

906
00:55:34,190 --> 00:55:37,692
So, I ask of you, everyone here today,

907
00:55:37,692 --> 00:55:40,474
help the world become a better tomorrow

908
00:55:40,474 --> 00:55:42,836
by thinking diversly about accessibility,

909
00:55:42,836 --> 00:55:45,277
and please do not leave any gamer behind.

910
00:55:45,277 --> 00:55:46,598
Thank you, I'm Sikil.

911
00:55:46,598 --> 00:55:46,919
Thank you.

912
00:55:46,919 --> 00:55:47,099
Thank you.

